why `get` ? what if there are no tokens? maybe `getOrElse(Nil)` would be better?
or something like this?
```scala
if(pipeInScope(pos, sourceText){
  val tokenized = source.toInput.tokenize.toOption
  tokenized.flatMap{ tokens => 
    tokens.collectFirst{ 
      case token: Constant.String if inToken(pos, token) && longString(sourceText, token) => 
        new TextEdit(range, indent(source.toInput, pos) + "|")
      }
  }
} else {
  None
}
```

Let's just return the `new TextEdit(...)` here. as a result, the `tokens.flatMap` on line 62 will be returning this edit.
```scala
if (pipeInScope(pos, sourceText)) {
  val tokens = Input.VirtualFile(...)
  tokens.flatMap { tokens => tokens.collectFirst{ case (...) if (...) => new TextEdit(...) } }
} else Future.successfull(None)
```
or we could do:
```scala
tokens match {
  case None => 
    Future.successful(None)
  case tokens => 
    tokens.collectFirst{ case (...) if (...) => new TextEdit(...) }
}
```

whatever you find more readable
